### TITLE ###
NotNullNarrowsTruthyBranch
### DESCRIPTION ###
`if x != null:` should narrow x to non-null inside the then-body.
Outside the if (no else, no early exit), x falls back to int? via join.
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int?):
    if x != null:
        y = x
    z = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int?
  y @ 3:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 3:13 -> int
  z @ 4:5 -> <no-type>
  x @ 4:9 -> int?

# Symbol types
  f (fn): fn(int?) -> void
  x (param): int?
  y (local): int
  z (local): int?

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
NullEqualReturnsNarrowsFallthrough
### DESCRIPTION ###
Guard pattern: `if x == null: return` leaves x as non-null in the
fall-through path.
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int?):
    if x == null:
        return
    y = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int?
  y @ 4:5 -> <no-type>
  x @ 4:9 -> int

# Symbol types
  f (fn): fn(int?) -> void
  x (param): int?
  y (local): int

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
NoNullableBaseTypeNoNarrowing
### DESCRIPTION ###
x is int (no nullable component); the predicate has nothing to refine.
The if/else still produces a clean join.
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int):
    if x != null:
        y = x
    else:
        z = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int
  y @ 3:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 3:13 -> int
  z @ 5:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 5:13 -> int

# Symbol types
  f (fn): fn(int) -> void
  x (param): int
  y (local): int
  z (local): int

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
NullLiteralRejectedByNonNullableSlot
### DESCRIPTION ###
The null literal synthesizes to TypingNullT, which is only
assignable to slots that admit null. A bare `a: int = null`
fires a type-mismatch diagnostic.
### INPUT ###
a: int = null
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  a @ 1:1 -> <no-type>

# Symbol types
  a (local): int

# Diagnostics
  [hint] RAD30001 @ 1:10 - Value of type 'null' is not assignable to declared type 'int'
### TITLE ###
NullLiteralAcceptedByOptionalSlot
### DESCRIPTION ###
TypingNullT flows freely into T? slots.
### INPUT ###
a: int? = null
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  a @ 1:1 -> <no-type>

# Symbol types
  a (local): int?

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
NotNullElseNarrowsToNull
### DESCRIPTION ###
The else branch of `if x != null:` narrows x to TypingNullT
(definite null). Regression lock against the previous no-op,
which left x typed as the un-narrowed `int?`.
### INPUT ###
fn f(x: int?):
    if x != null:
        a = x
    else:
        b = x
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  x @ 2:8 -> int?
  a @ 3:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 3:13 -> int
  b @ 5:9 -> <no-type>
  x @ 5:13 -> null

# Symbol types
  a (local): int
  b (local): null
  f (fn): fn(int?) -> void
  x (param): int?

# Diagnostics
  (none)
### TITLE ###
InferredReturnMixingValueAndNullProducesOptional
### DESCRIPTION ###
A fn that returns 5 in one branch and null in another should
synthesize to `int?`, the canonical nullable form. Previously
this produced `int|dynamic` because null synth fell back to
Dynamic.
### INPUT ###
fn maybe(b: bool):
    if b:
        return 5
    return null
### STDOUT ###
# Identifier types
  b @ 2:8 -> bool

# Symbol types
  b (param): bool
  maybe (fn): fn(bool) -> int?

# Diagnostics
  (none)
